      <hedline>
        <hl1>Hypocrisy on Tires</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Demaree Barnes letter finds it curious that Republicans are lambasting transportation officials in Firestone tire debacle; asks what happened to Republican theme song decrying 'bureaucratic intrusion' (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It is curious to hear Senator John McCain and other Republicans lambaste the secretary of transportation for being delinquent in the Firestone tire debacle (Business Day, Sept. 13).  What happened to the Republican theme song decrying ''bureaucratic intrusion'' into private corporate affairs by federal agencies?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It is curious to hear Senator John McCain and other Republicans lambaste the secretary of transportation for being delinquent in the Firestone tire debacle (Business Day, Sept. 13).  What happened to the Republican theme song decrying ''bureaucratic intrusion'' into private corporate affairs by federal agencies?</p>
        <p>This matter shows the ridiculousness of the Republican position that government regulation of private enterprise is unnecessary (and somehow immoral). The fact is that unbridled competitive enterprise is not  always sound public policy and does not always benefit the public.</p>
        <p>DEMAREE BARNES  White Plains, Sept. 13, 2000</p>
      </block>
